abstract: Evin Prison, in Tehran, houses hundreds of dissidents and political prisoners. Witnesses described hearing gunshots and explosions as a blaze made its way through the facility on Saturday.
snippet: Evin Prison, in Tehran, houses hundreds of dissidents and political prisoners. Witnesses described hearing gunshots and explosions as a blaze made its way through the facility on Saturday.
lead_paragraph: A massive fire broke out on Saturday at Evin prison, the notorious detention facility in Iran’s capital where hundreds of dissidents and political prisoners are held, as anti-regime protests roiled the country for a fifth week. As the fire raged, the sounds of explosions and gunfire could be heard in the neighborhood near the prison, according to witnesses and videos posted to social media.

main: Fire Erupts at Iran’s Most Notorious Prison Amid National Protests
print_headline: Fire Erupts at Prison Housing Dissidents in Iran

abstract: A mountain retreat in Idyllwild, a 2006 ranch house in San Miguel and a Craftsman bungalow in San Diego.
snippet: A mountain retreat in Idyllwild, a 2006 ranch house in San Miguel and a Craftsman bungalow in San Diego.
lead_paragraph: This house is made from old-growth redwood, with windows and decks facing the hills and, in the distance, Tahquitz Peak, one of the highest points in the San Bernardino Mountains. Idyllwild, a community in the San Jacinto Mountains, feels remote, with bed-and-breakfasts, a handful of restaurants and a year-round population of weekenders, many based in Los Angeles or San Diego.

abstract: The girls and women of anime tend to experience the conflicting emotions of real life. That’s because the auteurs try to create “an everyday, real person.”
snippet: The girls and women of anime tend to experience the conflicting emotions of real life. That’s because the auteurs try to create “an everyday, real person.”
lead_paragraph: At a time of widespread debate over the depiction of women in film, the top Japanese animators have long been creating heroines who are more layered and complex than many of their American counterparts. They have faults and weaknesses and tempers as well as strengths and talents. They’re not properties or franchises; they’re characters the filmmakers believe in.

main: For the Most Complex Heroines in Animation, Look to Japan

abstract: Hugh Jackman plays the father of a troubled teenager in Florian Zeller’s leaden drama.
snippet: Hugh Jackman plays the father of a troubled teenager in Florian Zeller’s leaden drama.
lead_paragraph: At one point in “The Son,” directed by Florian Zeller and based on his play of the same name, a clinician briefs a divorced mother and father on their teenage son’s condition after a mental health emergency. “He’s in very good hands now,” the doctor says, referring to the hospital staff. “Now” is the key word; the implication is that the wealthy, well-meaning Peter (Hugh Jackman) and Kate (Laura Dern) are unfit to handle the issues their son Nicholas (Zen McGrath) is facing.

main: ‘The Son’ Review: Father Doesn’t Know Best

abstract: At a moment when experts say Iran is, again, on the verge of possessing enough fuel for a bomb, the dismantling of U.N. cameras was a sign of worsening prospects for the 2015 deal.
snippet: At a moment when experts say Iran is, again, on the verge of possessing enough fuel for a bomb, the dismantling of U.N. cameras was a sign of worsening prospects for the 2015 deal.
lead_paragraph: Iran began dismantling the U.N. monitoring system of its nuclear program this week, partly blinding nuclear inspectors in apparent retaliation for a resolution condemning its lack of cooperation with international inspectors, just at a moment when Tehran is again on the verge of possessing enough fuel for a bomb.
